üìò Security Concepts ‚Äì PG-DITISS (Aug 2025)
Session 12: Password Attacks & Countermeasures, Trojans, Spyware, Covert Channels
üîπ BASIC MCQs (10)
1. Password-cracking countermeasures mainly aim to:
A. Speed up login
B. Prevent unauthorized access
C. Improve UI
D. Increase bandwidth

2. Which is a STRONG password countermeasure?
A. Short passwords
B. Dictionary words
C. Password complexity & length
D. Reusing passwords

3. Active online password attack means:
A. Stealing hashes offline
B. Trying passwords directly on live system
C. Using rainbow tables
D. Capturing packets only

4. Passive online attacks involve:
A. Sending login requests
B. Sniffing credentials
C. Brute forcing
D. Locking accounts

5. Offline password attacks are performed on:
A. Live authentication system
B. Password hash files
C. Web server
D. Firewall

6. Keyloggers are used to:
A. Encrypt keystrokes
B. Record keystrokes
C. Block keyboard
D. Detect malware

7. Spyware mainly aims to:
A. Crash system
B. Monitor user activity secretly
C. Improve performance
D. Encrypt files

8. A Trojan is best described as:
A. Self-replicating malware
B. Legitimate-looking malicious program
C. Network attack
D. Hardware threat

9. Backdoors allow attackers to:
A. Improve authentication
B. Bypass normal security
C. Encrypt traffic
D. Update OS

10. Overt channels are:
A. Hidden communication paths
B. Legitimate communication channels
C. Encrypted tunnels
D. Malware channels

üî∏ INTERMEDIATE MCQs (10)
11. Which countermeasure limits online password attacks?
A. Hashing
B. Account lockout
C. Salting
D. Encryption

12. Offline attacks are MORE dangerous because they:
A. Are slower
B. Bypass account lockout
C. Require internet
D. Need user interaction

13. Salting passwords helps prevent:
A. Brute force
B. Rainbow table attacks
C. Keylogging
D. DoS

14. Keyloggers are classified as:
A. Hardware only
B. Software only
C. Hardware and software
D. Network devices

15. Trojans differ from worms because Trojans:
A. Self-replicate
B. Need user execution
C. Spread automatically
D. Target networks only

16. Covert channels are used to:
A. Improve bandwidth
B. Hide data transmission
C. Block communication
D. Detect malware

17. Reverse-connecting Trojans are dangerous because they:
A. Use UDP
B. Bypass firewall restrictions
C. Use encryption
D. Are open source

18. Netcat Trojan is mainly used for:
A. Packet sniffing
B. Backdoor creation
C. Password hashing
D. Encryption

19. Indications of Trojan infection include:
A. Faster system
B. Unexpected network connections
C. Improved performance
D. Lower CPU usage

20. Kali Linux is mainly used in lab for:
A. Software development
B. Password cracking & security testing
C. Video editing
D. Game design

üî∫ ADVANCED MCQs (10) ‚Äì CCEE TRAP + LAB FOCUS
21. Which attack is MOST affected by account lockout policies?
A. Offline brute force
B. Online brute force
C. Rainbow table
D. Dictionary offline

22. Offline password cracking usually requires access to:
A. Login page
B. Password hashes
C. Firewall rules
D. User session

23. Why keyloggers bypass strong passwords?
A. Encrypt keystrokes
B. Capture credentials before hashing
C. Break encryption
D. Modify OS

24. A Trojan communicating over DNS is an example of:
A. Overt channel
B. Covert channel
C. Encrypted tunnel
D. MITM

25. Reverse shell Trojans initiate connection from:
A. Attacker to victim
B. Victim to attacker
C. Firewall to victim
D. Server to client

26. Which malware type maintains long-term unauthorized access?
A. Virus
B. Worm
C. Backdoor
D. Adware

27. Netcat becomes a Trojan when it is used to:
A. Scan ports
B. Transfer files normally
C. Provide unauthorized shell access
D. Capture packets

28. Which indicator MOST strongly suggests covert channel activity?
A. High CPU usage
B. Legitimate protocol carrying hidden data
C. Application crash
D. Disk failure

29. Strong password storage should include:
A. Plain text
B. Hashing only
C. Hashing + salting
D. Encryption only

30. Session 12 mainly tests understanding of:
A. UI design
B. Password attacks + malware behavior
C. Database optimization
D. Hardware troubleshooting

